  <p class="footnotetext"><a href="#_ftnref1" name="_ftn1" class="fn" id="_ftn1">[1]</a> Rule 1.8 is entitled "Conflict
  of Interest: Prohibited Transactions" and provides in pertinent part:</p>

  <blockquote>
    <p class="footnotetext">* * *</p>

    <p class="footnotetext">(h) A lawyer shall not make an agreement prospectively limiting the lawyer's liability to a
    client for malpractice unless permitted by law and the client is independently represented in making the agreement,
    or settle a claim for such liability with an unrepresented client or former client without first advising that
    person in writing that independent representation is appropriate in connection therewith.</p>

    <p class="footnotetext">* * *</p>
  </blockquote>

  <p class="footnotetext"><a href="#_ftnref2" name="_ftn2" class="fn" id="_ftn2">[2]</a> According to the ABA
  Standards, negligence is "the failure of a lawyer to heed a substantial risk that circumstances exist or that a
  result will follow, which failure is a deviation from the standard of care that a reasonable lawyer would exercise in
  the situation." Knowledge is defined as "the conscious awareness of the nature or attendant circumstances of the
  conduct but without the conscious objective or purpose to accomplish a particular result." Intent is defined as "the
  conscious objective or purpose to accomplish a particular result."</p>

  <p class="footnotetext"><a href="#_ftnref3" name="_ftn3" class="fn" id="_ftn3">[3]</a> In its concurrence, ODC
  states:</p>

  <blockquote>
    <p class="footnotetext">While the rule violation exposed the client to potential harm, the facts appear to be that
    the client received $8,000.00, her medical expenses were paid by the Respondent, and the Respondent bore the court
    costs. Considering the nature of the client's personal injury claim, a slip and fall in a Wal-Mart store, it is
    certainly arguable that the end result here for the Complainant is that she probably received more money than she
    might have if the case had proceeded normally. While this in no way excuses the Respondent's misconduct, it does
    argue against actual harm to the Complainant.</p>
  </blockquote>

  <p class="footnotetext">ODC's Concurrence, p. 2.</p>

  <p class="footnotetext"><a href="#_ftnref4" name="_ftn4" class="fn" id="_ftn4">[4]</a> ABA <i>Standards for Imposing
  Lawyer Sanctions</i>, Standard 9.22(i). Respondent was admitted to practice law in Louisiana in 1991.</p>

  <p class="footnotetext"><a href="#_ftnref5" name="_ftn5" class="fn" id="_ftn5">[5]</a> In the matter of <i>In re
  White</i>, Board Docket No. 96-DB-002, the Board concluded that as the Board is the permanent statewide agency which
  administers the lawyer disciplinary system, and, as such, the agency which maintains records of all such discipline,
  it may take judicial notice of a respondent's prior disciplinary record.</p>

  <p class="footnotetext"><a href="#_ftnref6" name="_ftn6" class="fn" id="_ftn6">[6]</a> ABA <i>Standards for Imposing
  Lawyer Sanctions</i>, Standard 9.22(a).</p>

  <p class="footnotetext"><a href="#_ftnref7" name="_ftn7" class="fn" id="_ftn7">[7]</a> <i>Id.</i>, Standards 9.32(b)
  and (e).</p>

  <p class="footnotetext"><a href="#_ftnref8" name="_ftn8" class="fn" id="_ftn8">[8]</a> Dunn was also found to have
  violated Rules 1.3 (lack of due diligence); 8.4(a) (violating the Rules of Professional Conduct); 8.4(c) (engaging in
  conduct involving fraud, deceit, dishonesty or misrepresentation); and 8.4(d) (engaging in conduct prejudicial to the
  administration of justice).</p>

  <p class="footnotetext"><a href="#_ftnref9" name="_ftn9" class="fn" id="_ftn9">[9]</a> Aggravating factors included:
  <span class="ABAstandard">substantial experience in the practice of law</span>, <span class="ABAstandard">prior
  discipline</span>, <span class="ABAstandard">selfish motive</span>, <span class="ABAstandard">pattern of
  conduct</span>, and <span class="ABAstandard">vulnerability of the victim</span>.</p>
